            <section class="prose">
              <h2>What is DTI ratio?</h2>
              <p>
                Your debt-to-income (DTI) ratio compares how much you owe each
                month to how much you earn. Lenders use it to judge how
                comfortably you can take on a new loan or mortgage payment.
              </p>
              <p>There are two main versions:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Front-end DTI</strong> – housing costs only (rent or
                  mortgage + taxes/insurance/HOA) divided by income.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Back-end DTI</strong> – housing costs
                  <em>plus</em> all other monthly debts divided by income.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Front-end DTI formula</p>
                <p>
                  Front-end DTI (%) = (Monthly housing costs ÷ Gross monthly
                  income) × 100
                </p>
                <p class="font-semibold mt-3 mb-1">Back-end DTI formula</p>
                <p>
                  Back-end DTI (%) = (Monthly housing costs + Other monthly
                  debts ÷ Gross monthly income) × 100
                </p>
              </div>

              <h2>Typical lender DTI guidelines</h2>
              <p>
                Guidelines vary by lender and loan program, but these ranges are
                common:
              </p>
              <div class="overflow-x-auto">
                <table class="min-w-full text-sm border border-gray-200">
                  <thead class="bg-gray-50">
                    <tr>
                      <th class="px-3 py-2 text-left">Back-end DTI range</th>
                      <th class="px-3 py-2 text-left">
                        How lenders may view it
                      </th>
                    </tr>
                  </thead>
                  <tbody>
                    <tr class="border-t">
                      <td class="px-3 py-2">
                        <span
                          class="range-badge bg-emerald-100 text-emerald-800"
                          >≤ 30%</span
                        >
                      </td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2">
                        Excellent. Plenty of room in your budget; strong for
                        most loans.
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr class="border-t">
                      <td class="px-3 py-2">
                        <span class="range-badge bg-green-100 text-green-800"
                          >31–36%</span
                        >
                      </td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2">
                        Good. Typically acceptable for conventional mortgages.
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr class="border-t">
                      <td class="px-3 py-2">
                        <span class="range-badge bg-yellow-100 text-yellow-800"
                          >37–43%</span
                        >
                      </td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2">
                        Borderline. Often still approved, especially with strong
                        credit and savings.
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr class="border-t">
                      <td class="px-3 py-2">
                        <span class="range-badge bg-orange-100 text-orange-800"
                          >44–50%</span
                        >
                      </td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2">
                        High. Some programs allow this, but you may face tighter
                        conditions or higher rates.
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                    <tr class="border-t">
                      <td class="px-3 py-2">
                        <span class="range-badge bg-red-100 text-red-800"
                          >&gt; 50%</span
                        >
                      </td>
                      <td class="px-3 py-2">
                        Very high. Approval becomes difficult; focus on reducing
                        debt or increasing income.
                      </td>
                    </tr>
                  </tbody>
                </table>
              </div>

              <h2>What counts as debt in DTI?</h2>
              <p>Include these in your monthly debt payments:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Rent or mortgage payment (principal &amp; interest)</li>
                <li>
                  Property taxes, homeowners insurance, mortgage insurance, HOA
                  dues
                </li>
                <li>Car loans and leases</li>
                <li>
                  Student loans (use the required payment, or lender’s assumed
                  payment if inment)
                </li>
                <li>Personal loans and installment loans</li>
                <li>Credit card minimum payments</li>
                <li>
                  Other court-ordered or documented obligations (e.g., alimony,
                  child support)
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>Do <strong>not</strong> include:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Utilities (electricity, gas, water, internet)</li>
                <li>Groceries, gas, and everyday spending</li>
                <li>
                  Health insurance premiums (unless a lender specifically asks)
                </li>
                <li>Subscriptions and discretionary spending</li>
              </ul>

              <h2>Step-by-step: how to calculate your DTI manually</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>List your gross monthly income.</strong> Include
                  salary, bonuses, commissions, and other regular income you can
                  document.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>List each monthly debt payment.</strong> Use the
                  required minimum payment, not what you usually pay.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Add up housing costs</strong> to get your total
                  monthly housing payment.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Add up housing + all other debts</strong> to get your
                  total monthly debt payment.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong
                    >Divide each total by your gross monthly income</strong
                  >
                  and multiply by 100 to get percentages.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>How to improve a high DTI ratio</h2>
              <p>If your DTI is higher than lenders prefer, you can:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Pay down revolving debt</strong> like credit cards to
                  reduce minimum payments.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Consolidate or refinance loans</strong> to lower your
                  monthly obligations.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Avoid taking on new debt</strong> before applying for
                  a mortgage or major loan.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Increase your income</strong> through overtime, side
                  work, or a second job.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Consider a smaller loan amount</strong> or lower
                  housing payment to bring DTI into range.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                Use the toggles and sliders in this calculator to test different
                payoff and income scenarios before you apply.
              </p>
            </section>

            <section class="mt-8" id="faq">
              <h2 class="text-xl font-semibold mb-4">DTI Ratio FAQs</h2>
              <div class="space-y-3">
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    What is a good DTI ratio?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    Many lenders like to see a back-end DTI of 36% or less, and
                    a front-end DTI of 28% or less. Some mortgage programs will
                    approve DTIs up to about 43–50% if you have strong credit,
                    stable income, and extra savings.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Does DTI affect my credit score?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    DTI itself is not part of your credit score, but it strongly
                    affects loan approvals and interest rates. Credit scores
                    look at your credit utilization (balances vs. limits),
                    payment history, and other factors, while DTI compares your
                    total monthly debts to your income.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    Is DTI calculated per person or per household?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    For joint applications, lenders usually combine both
                    borrowers’ qualifying income and debts to calculate a single
                    household DTI. For an individual application, they use only
                    that borrower’s income and debts, even if there are other
                    earners in the household.
                  </p>
                </details>
                <details class="border border-gray-200 rounded-md p-3">
                  <summary class="font-medium cursor-pointer">
                    How often should I check my DTI?
                  </summary>
                  <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-700">
                    It’s useful to check your DTI whenever you’re planning a
                    major purchase (home, car, personal loan) or if your income
                    or debts change significantly. Tracking it a few times per
                    year can help you stay on top of your overall financial
                    health.
                  </p>
                </details>
              </div>
            </section>
